CO2 Emission Over Time by Continent¶

In [10]:
# Make df pipeline interactive
idf = df.interactive()

#Define Panel widgets
year_slider = pn.widgets.IntSlider(name='year slider', start=1960, end=2021, step=5, value=1970)

#Radio buttons for C02 measures
yaxis_co2 = pn.widgets.RadioButtonGroup(
    name='Y axis',
    options=['co2', 'co2_per_capita'],
    button_type='success'
)
In [11]:
continents = ['World','Asia','Africa','Oceana','Europe','Antarctica', 'North America','South America']

co2_pipeline = (
    idf[
        (idf.year <= year_slider) & (idf.country.isin(continents))
    ]
    .groupby(['country', 'year'])[yaxis_co2].mean()
    .to_frame()
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values(by='year')
    .reset_index(drop=True)
)
In [28]:
co2_table = co2_pipeline.pipe(

    page_size=12, 
    sizing_mode='stretch_width'
)

Summary¶

This line chart presents a historical overview of carbon emissions on different continents from 1960 to 2021. Each continent is represented by a distinct line on the chart, and the y-axis measures the total carbon emissions in metric tons. Over the six-decade period, viewers can observe the changing trends in emissions, identifying which continents have experienced increases, decreases, or stability in their carbon output. This visualization highlights the evolution of carbon emissions on a global scale and can be used to assess the impact of environmental policies and industrialization trends across continents over time.
